#, no-wrap
msgid "How to use git-daemon"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/howto/use-git-daemon.txt:9
msgid ""
"Git can be run in inetd mode and in stand alone mode. But all you want is "
"let a coworker pull from you, and therefore need to set up a Git server real "
"quick, right?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/howto/use-git-daemon.txt:12
msgid ""
"Note that git-daemon is not really chatty at the moment, especially when "
"things do not go according to plan (e.g. a socket could not be bound)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/howto/use-git-daemon.txt:14
msgid "Another word of warning: if you run"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/howto/use-git-daemon.txt:16 ../Documentation/howto/use-git-daemon.txt:53
#, no-wrap
msgid "\t$ git ls-remote git://127.0.0.1/rule-the-world.git\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/howto/use-git-daemon.txt:18
msgid "and you see a message like"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/howto/use-git-daemon.txt:20
#, no-wrap
msgid "\tfatal: The remote end hung up unexpectedly\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/howto/use-git-daemon.txt:25
msgid ""
"it only means that _something_ went wrong. To find out _what_ went wrong, "
"you have to ask the server. (Git refuses to be more precise for your "
"security only. Take off your shoes now. You have any coins in your pockets? "
"Sorry, not allowed -- who knows what you planned to do with them?)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/howto/use-git-daemon.txt:27
msgid "With these two caveats, let's see an example:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/howto/use-git-daemon.txt:30
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\t$ git daemon --reuseaddr --verbose --base-path=/home/gitte/git \\\n"
"\t  --export-all -- /home/gitte/git/rule-the-world.git\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/howto/use-git-daemon.txt:34
msgid ""
"(Of course, unless your user name is `gitte` _and_ your repository is in "
"~/rule-the-world.git, you have to adjust the paths. If your repository is "
"not bare, be aware that you have to type the path to the .git directory!)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/howto/use-git-daemon.txt:38
msgid ""
"This invocation tries to reuse the address if it is already taken (this can "
"save you some debugging, because otherwise killing and restarting git-daemon "
"could just silently fail to bind to a socket)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/howto/use-git-daemon.txt:42
msgid ""
"Also, it is (relatively) verbose when somebody actually connects to it.  It "
"also sets the base path, which means that all the projects which can be "
"accessed using this daemon have to reside in or under that path."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/howto/use-git-daemon.txt:46
msgid ""
"The option `--export-all` just means that you _don't_ have to create a file "
"named `git-daemon-export-ok` in each exported repository. (Otherwise, "
"git-daemon would complain loudly, and refuse to cooperate.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/howto/use-git-daemon.txt:49
msgid ""
"Last of all, the repository which should be exported is specified. It is a "
"good practice to put the paths after a \"--\" separator."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/howto/use-git-daemon.txt:51
msgid "Now, test your daemon with"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
